This is the perfect time to pull the camera back and look at the macro-structure. At Session 18-20, you are exiting the "Sandbox" of Act II/Early Act III. The world is reacting to them, but soon, they must react to the end of the world.
To "stick the landing" at Session 45, we need to funnel these disparate, chaotic threads (Valerius, the Plagues, the Civil War, the personal corruptions) into a single, overwhelming narrative spearhead aimed directly at Alduin.
Here is the Architectural Roadmap for the Second Half of the Campaign, detailing the "Must-Happen" milestones that get them from their current crossroads to the skies of Sovngarde.

PHASE 1: THE BLUEPRINT OF DEFEAT (Sessions 20-25)
The party learns HOW to kill a god, and realizes they lack the tools.
1. The Esbern Funnel (Sky Haven Temple)
Regardless of which of the "Three Fires" they tackle first, Esbern's questline must eventually take priority. They must secure the Dragonstone (from Bleak Falls Barrow) to map the Dragon Cult's resurrection network.
This map leads them and Esbern to the Reach, where they unlock Sky Haven Temple.
The Big Reveal: Alduin's Wall. Esbern translates it. It explicitly states that to defeat Alduin, they need three things: Paarthurnax, the Elder Scroll, and the Dragonrend Shout.
The Catch: The wall depicts the Dragonborn doing this. Esbern reiterates the terrifying truth: "We don't have one."
2. The Greybeard Gate (High Hrothgar)
The party must climb the 7,000 Steps to meet Master Arngeir and Paarthurnax.
The Moral Test: They are judged by the Greybeards. (The monks will be horrified by the party's vampirism, necromancy, and Daedric taints, making this a brutal social encounter).
The Lore Drop: Paarthurnax agrees to help them find the Elder Scroll, but delivers the crushing truth: Mortals cannot safely read an Elder Scroll or instantly master a Shout like Dragonrend. Without a Dragon Soul to anchor the mind, the Scroll will shatter their sanity, and the Shout will tear them apart.
PHASE 2: THE MORTAL LIMIT (Sessions 26-32)
The party hits a hard wall. They know what to do, but are biologically incapable of doing it. Meanwhile, their personal arcs reach their apex.
1. The Apex Transformations
While desperately searching for a way around the "Mortal Limit," the party's personal corruptions hit critical mass:
Alfonso (The Vrykolas Lord): Must consume the heart of a Dragon Priest (Rahgot) or a Vampire Lord (Valerius) to achieve his final, horrifying Apotheosis.
Davinia (The Winter Queen): Reaches CDI 0.5 (Point of Irreversibility). She must either purge Ismara (via Hermaeus Mora or the Eldergleam roots) or fully succumb to the Crown, becoming an emotionless deity of stasis.
Kyboh (The Echo Mimic): Hjolmar unleashes his perfect, soulless clone. Kyboh must fight a shadow war against his own "optimized" self.
Orion (The Double Agent): Receives the Dark Brotherhood contract to Kill the Emperor. Valerius orders him to sabotage it. He must finally choose a master.
Saijah (The Apex Predator): Must choose between the long, hard path of Kynareth (cleansing the Dagon corruption) or accepting Hircine's gift of Alpha Lycanthropy to slaughter the cultists efficiently.
2. The Fall of Krusp Fanck
Krusp, fighting a lonely war against the Dragon Priests, also hits the Mortal Limit. Seeing the world burning (partially due to Alfonso's plagues and the party's actions), his oath to protect the innocent breaks him.
The Tragic Choice: To save the world, the Ashen Blade abandons his absolute rule ("Daedric power is a lie"). Off-screen, he seeks out Mehrunes' Razor and performs the Mankar Camoran ritual. He carves away his humanity to shape his soul into a dragon's.
He becomes a False Dragonborn.
PHASE 3: THE IMPOSSIBLE CHOICE (Sessions 33-38)
The party must find a way to read the Elder Scroll and learn Dragonrend before the world ends.
The Daedric Path vs. The Aedric Path
Through their scholarly research (or by discovering what Krusp did), the party realizes they only have two options to survive reading the Elder Scroll at the Time-Wound:
OPTION A (The Daedric Path - The Forgeries):
They hunt down Mehrunes' Razor. They stand at a Lorkhan-touched site. They explicitly speak aloud the piece of their humanity they are sacrificing (Honor, Love, Memory) and carve their own souls. They become False Dragonborns (taking permanent HP/FP penalties, gaining Shouts, but rolling on the catastrophic Soul Dissonance Table every time they use one).
OPTION B (The Aedric Path - The Revelation):
Through investigation into Bjorn's sudden youth, his impossible luck, and Davinia's Ismara Sight (seeing the massive, burning sun of a soul inside him), they piece it together. Old Bjorn is the unawakened Dragonborn.
The Catch: They have to force an old man who just wanted to drive a cart to step up and fulfill a destiny he ran away from 40 years ago.


PHASE 4: THE APOCALYPSE CONVERGENCE (Sessions 39-42)
The Clocks strike midnight.
1. The Time-Wound
The party (either as False Dragonborns, or escorting an awakened Bjorn) brings the Elder Scroll to the Throat of the World. They read it, witness the ancient heroes, and learn Dragonrend.
2. The World Unravels
Simultaneously, the enemy clocks hit Tier 5:
The Dagon Cult: The red sky appears. Daedra spill into Mundus.
The Dragon Cult: Morokei begins the Apotheosis Ritual at Labyrinthian, draining the College of Winterhold to turn the Dragon Priests into gods.
Alduin Attacks: Alduin descends on the Throat of the World. The party uses Dragonrend to ground him, but he is too strong. He flees to Sovngarde to gorge on the souls of the dead and recover.
3. Skuldafn (The Portal)
To follow Alduin, the party must assault the Dragon Cult's ultimate fortress: Skuldafn.
Here, they reunite with Krusp Fanck.
If they are False Dragonborns, he looks at them with bitter understanding: "We're damned together now."
He stays behind to hold the line against an army of Draugr and Dragons, sacrificing himself so the party can enter the portal to the afterlife.
PHASE 5: SOVNGARDE & THE LANDING (Sessions 43-45)
The Final Battle.
The party steps into the mists of Sovngarde. How this plays out depends entirely on the choice they made in Phase 3.
ENDING A: The Shield-Thanes (The Aedric Path)
They escorted Bjorn. The Ancient Nord Heroes (Hakon, Gormlaith, Felldir) recognize Bjorn as the true Dovahkiin and welcome him with open arms.
The party fights as Shield-Thanes. Bjorn uses Dragonrend to ground Alduin, the Ancient Heroes deal massive damage, and the party focuses on battlefield control, protecting Bjorn, and surviving Alduin's apocalyptic AoE attacks.
The Tone: Heroic, triumphant, but humbling. They saved the world by protecting the true hero.
ENDING B: The Alliance of the Damned (The Daedric Path)
They carved their souls. When they enter the Hall of Valor, the Ancient Nord Heroes are repulsed. "You are hollow mockeries. You defile this place. We will not aid abominations."
The Ancient Heroes turn their backs. The party must face Alduin alone.
The Tone: Brutal, desperate, terrifying. Every time they use Dragonrend, they risk blowing themselves up on the Soul Dissonance Table. They have no legendary backup. They must rely on their monstrous synergies (Alfonso's rot, Davinia's ice, Orion's vampirism, Saijah's fury, Kyboh's kinetic bombs) to drag a god down into the mud and beat him to death.
The Aftermath: They save the world, but they are forever marked, indebted to Daedric Princes, and rejected by the very legends they saved. A dark, hollow, but undeniably badass victory.

The Architect's Checklist (What you must enforce):
To make this ending work, you must ensure these seeds are planted over the next 10 sessions:
The Elder Scroll requires a Dragon Soul. Establish this limitation early via Esbern or Urag gro-Shub so it doesn't feel like a last-minute roadblock.
Bjorn's "Luck" must escalate. Keep hinting at his de-aging, his impossible fortitude, and the strange way reality bends to keep him safe.
Krusp's Despair. Let the party hear rumors of Krusp fighting alone, sounding more and more desperate as the plagues (that Alfonso helped create) ravage the land.
The Lure of the Daedra. Keep reminding the party that Daedric Princes (Namira, Peryite, Molag Bal, Hircine) offer shortcuts. Power now, pay later. This sets the thematic precedent for the soul-carving ritual.
