You are absolutely right. Having him die at the portal is a classic trope, but having him die in the boss fight, side-by-side with the very people he once condemned, is a much stronger emotional payoff. It allows him to see the mission through to the very end and delivers a far more devastating final character beat.
If he makes it to Sovngarde, his death shouldn't just be an HP drop; it needs to be a narrative spectacle that directly enables the party to win.
Here is how we architect "The Ashen Blade's Final Stand" to make it possible for him to join them, and to make his death the defining moment of the Alduin fight.

STEP 1: The Skuldafn Choice (How to bring him)
When the party arrives at Skuldafn, Krusp is preparing to make his suicide stand at the portal so the party can go through. To bring him with them, the party must actively choose to spend massive resources or call in their greatest favors to secure the gate so Krusp doesn't have to.
The Player Agency Checkpoint:
The players must provide an alternative "Wall" to hold back the Dragon Cult army.
The Faction Favor: If they gave the Jagged Crown to Galmar or the Empire, they can cash in their ultimate favor. The army they helped build arrives via a mountain pass just in time, charging the Draugr lines. Galmar (or a Legion Legate) shouts: "Go! We hold the line today!"
The Monstrous Sacrifice: If they have no army, a player must make a permanent sacrifice.
Alfonso might have to permanently sever his connection to his entire ghoul network, leaving them behind as a frenzied, uncontrolled mob to clog the pass.
Davinia might have to tap the Crown of the Pale Lady to its absolute maximum, permanently sacrificing 1 or 2 points of Maximum FP/HP to summon an unbreakable, eternal glacier over the temple stairs.
Kyboh might have to trigger a 3-stack or 4-stack Titan's Tithe explosion on the cliff face, triggering an avalanche that seals the pass but horribly wounds him right before the final boss.


The Result: The pass is sealed. Krusp looks at the party in shock. You didn't leave him behind. He nods, steps through the portal with them, and enters the afterlife.

STEP 2: The Rejection in the Mist
When they arrive in Sovngarde, Krusp’s tragedy deepens.
As a False Dragonborn, his soul is marked by Mehrunes Dagon (from the razor). When they approach the Hall of Valor, the sky clears, and the ancient heroes (Hakon, Gormlaith, Felldir) emerge.
If Bjorn is there, they welcome Bjorn.
But they look at Krusp (and the party, if they also carved their souls), and they raise their weapons.
The Dialogue:
Hakon One-Eye sneers, his spectral axe glowing. "You carry the stench of the Deadlands, False-Tongue. You have butchered your own spirit for power. You are not welcome in Shor's Hall."
Krusp, the man who lived his entire life with perfect honor, who only broke his rules to save the world, is barred from warrior heaven.
Krusp lowers his weapon. He looks at the Hall of Valor, the paradise he fought his whole life to earn, and accepts that he will never enter it. He turns back to the party. "They are right. My soul is forfeit. Let's finish the job before Dagon comes to collect it."

STEP 3: The Final Battle & The Sacrifice
Alduin is a raid boss. Mechanically, he has an "Invulnerable Phase" or an apocalyptic attack (like a massive Meteor Storm or Soul Snare) that threatens to wipe the entire party and devour Bjorn's soul.
The Crisis Point (Phase 2 or 3 of the Boss Fight):
Alduin takes to the sky. He begins inhaling the ambient mist of Sovngarde, charging an attack that the party simply cannot survive or mitigate. The ancient heroes are pinned down. Bjorn is suppressed. Alduin is about to win.
Krusp's Realization:
Krusp realizes that conventional attacks won't ground Alduin in time. He looks at his hands, glowing with the dark, corrupted energy of his False Dragonborn soul. He realizes the only thing powerful enough to break a god's invulnerability is a paradoxical, reality-breaking explosion.
He must deliberately trigger the worst consequence of the Soul Dissonance Table.
The Sacrifice (Read Aloud):
"Krusp Fanck looks at the sky. He looks at the Hall of Valor, then at Danica’s shield strapped to his back. He turns to you one last time, the Daedric light burning fiercely in his eyes.
'Daedric power is a lie,' he says, his voice cutting through the roar of the World-Eater. 'Let's see if it can lie to a god.'
He doesn't wait for your response. He charges forward, directly into the epicenter of Alduin's gathering storm. He draws a massive breath, pulling every ounce of his stolen, corrupted soul into his lungs. He doesn't try to control the Shout. He purposefully overclocks it, weaponizing the very curse that damned him.
'JOOR... ZAH... FRUL!'
The Dragonrend Shout tears from his throat, but it doesn't just hit Alduin—it catastrophically backfires. Krusp's forged soul detonates. A shockwave of pure, black-and-red Daedric anti-magic erupts, shattering the sky. The blast hits Alduin point-blank, ripping through his divine scales and tearing his wings.
Alduin screams—a sound of genuine, mortal agony—and crashes to the ground, permanently grounded, his invulnerability shattered.
Where Krusp stood, there is nothing. No body. No ash. Just the scorch mark of a man who burned his own soul to nothingness to give you a chance."

Why this is the perfect ending for him:
It completes his philosophy: He told the party “Daedric power is a lie.” In the end, he uses the "lie" (his false soul) to trick reality and break a god's armor.
It resolves the Sovngarde rejection: He knows he can't go to the Hall of Valor. He knows Dagon claims his soul upon death. By detonating his soul completely, he denies Dagon his prize. He ceases to exist entirely—the ultimate sacrifice.
It gives the players the kill: Krusp doesn't steal the final kill on Alduin. He breaks Alduin's shield/grounds him, leaving Alduin broken, furious, and vulnerable for the players to deliver the final, epic execution sequence.
It makes the players' choice at Skuldafn immensely rewarding. By saving him at the gate, they bought the key to winning the final battle.
