Here is the newly refined, finalized architecture for how the party reaches the power level to fight Alduin, and how the "Dragonborn" requirement functions.

1. THE KEYS TO REALITY (Why they still need Bjorn or Krusp)
To defeat Alduin, the party still faces two mechanical laws of the universe that they cannot bypass with their own powers:
Reading the Elder Scroll: Mortals go blind/mad. Only a Dragon Soul can anchor the mind to read the Time-Wound.
Dragonrend (Joor Zah Frul): A Shout that forces mortality onto an immortal. Only a Dragonborn (True or False) can learn it instantly and project it.
The Party's Choice:
The party themselves are the Weapons, but they need a Key to open the door and ground the god. They must bring either:
Old Bjorn (The True Key): They force him to awaken. He reads the scroll, learns the shout, and grounds Alduin.
Krusp Fanck (The False Key): Krusp is the tragedy here. Because he stubbornly refused Daedric corruption for so long, he has no patron to empower him. To become the "Key" the party needs, he alone must hunt down Mehrunes' Razor and carve his soul into a False Dragonborn.
2. THE APEX PANTHEON (How the Party Fights a God)
Instead of all becoming False Dragonborns, the players spend Act III and IV reaching the absolute zenith of their own personal corruptions/blessings. By the time they enter Sovngarde, they are no longer a standard adventuring party. They are a dark pantheon.
Here is how each member matches Alduin's divine power:
Alfonso: The Carrion King
The Power: He achieves the Vrykolas Lord transformation (the King of Compost) and wears the Jagged Crown of Namira.
Role in the Finale: The Metaphysical Shield. He uses the Crown to literally eat Alduin's apocalyptic Shouts out of the air, converting the world-ending magic into rot, and vomiting it back to strip Alduin's divine Damage Reduction.
Davinia: The Winter Queen
The Power: She crosses the Point of Irreversibility (CDI 1.0). Whether she fully merges with Ismara or masters the Crown's power through sheer will, she wields Ancient Atmoran Tonal Ice.
Role in the Finale: The Architect of the Battlefield. She uses her mastery of ice to physically alter the terrain of Sovngarde, creating unbreakable glacial barriers to protect the "Key" (Bjorn/Krusp) from Alduin's physical assaults and locking down the World-Eater's mobility.
Saijah: The Alpha or The Hierophant
The Power: She reaches the climax of her crossroads. She either fully embraces Hircine's gift (becoming an Alpha Werewolf, immune to fear, striking with the force of a mythological beast) or reaches the zenith of Kynareth (becoming an Avatar of the Green, capable of instantly healing catastrophic damage).
Role in the Finale: The Striker or The Lifeline. As the Alpha, she deals the raw physical damage necessary to crack Alduin's scales. As the Hierophant, she sustains the party through attacks that should instantly vaporize mortals.
Orion: The Usurper Prince
The Power: He overthrows Valerius Caelus. He doesn't just kill him; he takes his blood, his title, and his power, becoming a true Vampire Lord of the Cyrodiilic Order. Alternatively, he becomes the Night Mother's Silencer, armed with legendary tools of the Void.
Role in the Finale: The Executioner. Wielding mastery over blood, shadows, and illusion, he strikes at Alduin's vulnerabilities, using his supernatural speed and mist-forms to evade the god's wrath and deliver devastating, precision strikes to the dragon's eyes and throat.
