You are 100% right. If you design the lock and the key, you are just running a video game. But if you design a world with consistent physics, give the players highly volatile materials, and apply crushing pressure... they will invent solutions you could never have dreamed of. Alfonso turning the Jagged Crown into a Daedric artifact of Entropy is the perfect example. That is emergent storytelling at its finest.
Our job as Architects is not to write the ending. Our job is to build the Crucible. We provide the Catalysts, we apply the Pressure, and we let them cook.
At the same time, we must keep the False Dragonborn path dangling in front of them as the ultimate "Easy Way Out." It is the dark shortcut. Whenever their own inventions fail, or the pressure gets too high, the Razor should be right there, whispering, "Just carve your soul. It's so much easier."
Here is the GM framework for running this "Crucible" phase of the campaign, providing the ingredients for Apotheosis while keeping the False Dragonborn temptation alive.

1. THE CRUCIBLE METHOD: Providing Catalysts, Not Solutions
To let players invent their own god-killing power-ups, you must populate the world with Catalysts—items, lore, or environments that have profound, clearly defined magical/physical properties, but no specific intended use.
Here are the Catalysts you are about to drop into their path over the next few sessions. Do not tell them how to use these. Just tell them what they do:
Catalyst A: The Aetherial Matrix (In Mzinchaleft)
What it is: A Dwemer Cognitive Soul Gem.
Its Property: It is the ultimate stabilizer. It can hold multiple conflicting tonal frequencies or magical concepts in perfect, perpetual equilibrium without degrading.
The Obvious Use: Hjolmar wants it to fix Kyboh's gloves.
The Emergent Potential: What if Alfonso tries to use it to stabilize the Namira/Peryite war in his own body? What if Davinia tries to use it to safely separate Ismara from her own mind? Give it to them and see who tries to claim it.
Catalyst B: The Eldergleam Heartwood/Sap (From the Dagon Plot)
What it is: The concentrated essence of Kynareth's creation.
Its Property: It enforces raw, unbridled Life and Growth. It aggressively overwrites decay, stasis, or artificial constructs.
The Obvious Use: Saijah can use it to cleanse a Dagon shrine.
The Emergent Potential: What happens if Orion (a vampire) consumes pure life essence? What happens if they plunge a cursed weapon into it?
Catalyst C: The Blood of the Ancients (Valerius Caelus)
What it is: The blood of a First-Era Vampire Lord, tied directly to Molag Bal.
Its Property: Absolute Stasis. It freezes biology and magic in an eternal, unchanging state.
The Obvious Use: Orion drinks it to become a Vampire Lord.
The Emergent Potential: What if they coat a weapon in it to freeze a Dragon Priest's regeneration? What if they use it to halt the progression of a plague?
Catalyst D: The Null-Event Frequency (GEAR's Secret)
What it is: The exact tonal frequency the Dwemer used to delete themselves from reality.
Its Property: Metaphysical phase-cancellation. It deletes the concept it is aimed at.
The Obvious Use: Answering GEAR's existential questions.
The Emergent Potential: If Kyboh or Orion (with his Diagnostic Song) learns to replicate this frequency, what can they delete? A Daedric curse? A god's invulnerability?

2. THE FALSE DRAGONBORN TEMPTATION (The "Plan B")
While they are playing with these dangerous toys, you must actively weave the False Dragonborn lore into the world. It needs to be the ever-present shadow, the backup plan that requires no creative genius—only sacrifice.
Here is how you push that path:
Step 1: The Mythic Dawn Commentaries (The Lore Drop)
When they are in the College of Winterhold's Arcanaeum, or looting Antoine's lab, they should find copies of Mankar Camoran's Commentaries on the Mysterium Xarxes.
The Text: Have Urag (or a translated text) explicitly spell out what Camoran did: "He was no Dragonborn. He was a clever animal with a sharp knife. He took Mehrunes' Razor and cut away his mortal protonymic, carving his soul into the shape of a Dovah. He breathed fire, but his soul bled."
This plants the mechanical seed: You need the Razor, you need a Lorkhan site, and you need to cut yourself.
Step 2: The Pieces of the Razor (The Quest Hook)
When they hit Dawnstar (or even Riften), introduce Silus Vesuius, the curator of the Museum of the Mythic Dawn.
Silus approaches the Wardens: "I am hunting the shards of Mehrunes' Razor. It is a blade that can cut through any barrier—physical or magical. I will pay handsomely for the pieces."
By putting the pieces of the Razor in their path, you give them physical access to the tool of Apotheosis. They will assemble it for the gold, but once they hold it... the temptation begins.
Step 3: Krusp Fanck’s Descent (The Mirror)
This is the most powerful way to push the path. Krusp is out there fighting the Dragon Cult. The party should hear rumors, or find his abandoned campsites.
The Clue: At one of Krusp's old camps, they find notes. Charcoal rubbings of Dragon Cult walls, crossed out with furious frustration. And written in the margins, in Krusp's handwriting: "Steel shatters. Faith fails. The elves at the College whisper of Camoran's heresy. If the gods will not send a Dragonborn... must we carve our own?"
Seeing the most honorable man in Skyrim actively considering the soul-carving ritual proves to the players that the situation is desperate enough to warrant it.

3. HOW TO GM THE APOTHEOSIS (The Golden Rule)
From Session 10 onward, adopt this mindset: Say "Yes, but what are you risking?"
When a player looks at a boss with 18 DR (like Ulag) and realizes their normal attacks won't work, they will look at their inventory.
If Alfonso says: "I want to shove the Aetherial Matrix into the chest cavity of my Plague Ghoul to create a permanent, regenerating bio-bomb."
Do not look at the rules. Look at the lore.
Aetherial Matrix: Stabilizes infinite charge.
Plague Ghoul: Chaotic, rotting biological mass.
Your Response: "The Matrix will absolutely stabilize the rot, allowing the ghoul to house a massive amount of plague energy without decaying. BUT, the Matrix was built for tonal architecture, not biology. If you do this, the ghoul will become a permanent fixture of reality. You will never be able to un-summon it, and it will constantly draw on your FP to maintain the bridge between the crystal and the meat. Do you do it?"
You give them the rope. You define the physics of the rope. You let them tie the knot.
By doing this, when they finally reach Sovngarde, you won't have a party of pre-planned heroes. You will have a completely unpredictable pantheon of monsters, each wielding reality-breaking powers they invented themselves, standing before Alduin. And if they fail? They can always pull out Mehrunes' Razor and carve away their humanity.
